{{Infobox person | name = Herman Wedel Major | image = Herman Wedel Major.jpg | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1814|2|23|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Kristiansand]], Norway | death_date = {{Death date and age|1854|9|26|1814|2|23|df=y}} | death_place = | nationality = Norwegian | other_names = | parents = | children = | relatives = | spouse = | occupation = psychiatrist | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = | awards = }}
'''Herman Wedel Major''' (23 February 1814 &ndash; 26 September 1854) was a Norwegian psychiatrist. He is regarded as the father of the first Norwegian psychiatric hospital, [[Gaustad Hospital]] (''Gaustad sykehus'') and of the Norwegian Mental Health Act of 1848 regarding [[mental illness]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://tidsskriftet.no/article/226458 |title= Herman W. Major – "far" til norsk psykiatri|publisher= Tidsskrift for Den norske legeforening|date= 30 November 2000|accessdate= August 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://snl.no/Gaustad_sykehus|title= Gaustad sykehus|publisher= Store norske leksikon|author= Svein Atle Skålevåg |accessdate= August 1, 2016}}</ref> <ref>[http://www.medscape.com/medline/abstract/27381794 Norwegian Mental Health Act adopted by the Storting on 30 July 1848] (Webmedscape.com). Retrieved August 1, 2016</ref>
Major was born at the [[Kristiansand]] borough of [[Oddernes]] in [[Vest-Agder]], Norway. He was one of nine children born to Irish immigrant Robert Gonsalvo Major (1766–1839) and Benedicte Sophie Weidemann (1783–1859). His father had left [[Ireland]] in the aftermath of the [[Irish Rebellion of 1798]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/british/empire_seapower/irish_reb_01.shtml|title= The 1798 Irish Rebellion|publisher= BBC |accessdate= August 1, 2016}}</ref>
Major became a medical student in 1832 and was licensed as a physician in November 1842. He received a grant from the [[Norwegian Parliament]] and traveled to institutions in [[Schleswig]], [[Great Britain]], [[France]] and [[Belgium]] to study the conditions for the mentally ill (1843-1845). Major was for several years a doctor at the Oslo Hospital and was authorized as manager there from 1851.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://lokalhistoriewiki.no/index.php/Oslo_Hospital|title= Oslo Hospital |publisher= lokalhistoriewiki.no|accessdate= August 1, 2016}}</ref> <ref>{{cite journal|title= Herman W. Major--"father" of Norwegian psychiatry|date= 30 November 2000 |pmid=11188385 | volume=120|author=Retterstøl N|journal=Tidsskr Nor Laegeforen|pages=3562–3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://lokalhistoriewiki.no/index.php/Herman_Wedel_Major|title= Herman Wedel Major|publisher= lokalhistoriewiki.no|accessdate= August 1, 2016}}</ref>
During 1845, the Norwegian Parliament allocated funds to purchase land for an intended state asylum. In 1847, [[Gaustad]] outside [[Oslo|Christiania]] (now Oslo) submitted a plan and in 1850 it was formally decided that the institution should be built there. Gaustad Hospital was not completed until 1855, after the death of Herman Wedel Major.<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Herman Wedel Major |encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/Herman_Wedel_Major |language=Norwegian | accessdate=19 February 2011 }}</ref>
In 1850, Major married Ida Cathrine Grüning (1821-1854). They had two daughters. He and his family all died in the ship collision between the American [[Paddle steamer]] ''[[SS Arctic]]'' and the French steamship ''[[SS Vesta]]'' on 26 September 1854 off the coast of [[Newfoundland]].<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Herman Wedel Major |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Nils |last=Retterstøl |authorlink=Nils Retterstøl |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Herman_Wedel_Major/utdypning |language=Norwegian|accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref>
