'''Mania errabunda''' or ''Restless madness'' is a name for the tendency of senile people (usually elderly) to wander aimlessly away from home. The name is not much used now.<ref>{{cite book|last=Browne, LLD|first=W. A. F.|authorlink=William A. F. Browne|title=The Journal of psychological medicine and mental pathology, Volume 5|editor=Forbes Winslow|editorlink=L. Forbes Winslow|date=1881|pages=216-221|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=mvkEAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA216&lpg=PA216&dq=Mania+errabunda}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Campbell|first=Robert Jean|title=Campbell's psychiatric dictionary|publisher=Oxford University Press US|date=2004|edition=8th, rev.|page=387|isbn=0195152212|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=Vrlsos_O13UC&pg=PA387&lpg=PA387&dq=Mania+errabunda}}</ref> The term is also used in conjunction with drug abuse and alcoholism.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Berkley|first=Henry J.|date=April 1897|title=MANIA ERRABUNDA (ALCOHOLIC DUAL CONSCIOUSNESS)|journal=[[American Journal of Insanity]]|issue=53|pages=489-509|url=https://ajp.psychiatryonline.org/doi/abs/10.1176/ajp.53.4.489|doi=10.1176/ajp.53.4.489}}</ref>
== In fiction == *Sir Walter Scott's ''[[The Fair Maid of Perth]]''. Browne says that the flight of Conacher is similar.<ref>Browne p. 218</ref>
