'''MedAccred''' is an accreditation program for critical process manufacturing operations in the production of [[medical devices]]<ref>{{cite web|title=MedAccred to track medical industry standards {{!}} Plastics News|url=http://www.plasticsnews.com/article/20160708/NEWS/160709865/medaccred-to-track-medical-industry-standards|website=www.plasticsnews.com|accessdate=15 August 2016}}</ref> MedAccred is an industry managed program with the medical device industry having responsibility for all decisions regarding program operations, development, and the decision to award accreditations. The MedAccred program is administered on behalf of the medical device industry by the Performance Review Institute (PRI), a not-for-profit affiliate of [[SAE International]]. Participants in the MedAccred program consist of medical device [[OEMs]], [[contract manufacturer]]s and suppliers who work together to develop industry-wide audit criteria and provide accreditation of critical manufacturing process suppliers to improve product quality.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}

== History ==

MedAccred was created following a medical device industry roundtable in held in [[Chicago]], IL in December 2012.  Companies present at the roundtable included [[Abbot Laboratories]], [[Baxter International]], [[Beckman Coulter]], [[Boston Scientific]], Brunk Industries, [[DePuy|DePuy Synthes]], [[GE Healthcare]], [[Medtronic]], Paragon Medical, [[Philips]], [[Stryker]], Symmetry Medical, [[Terumo|Terumo Cardiovascular Systems]] and [[Zimmer Biomet]].  Proof of concept audits based on the [[Nadcap]] program audit criteria were conducted in 2013.  Briefings on the MedAccred program were held with the [[FDA]] [[Center for Devices and Radiological Health|Center for Devices and Radiological Health’s (CDRH)]] Office of Compliance and the FDA’s Office of Global Operations within the Office of the Commissioner.The initial subscribing companies were [[Johnson & Johnson]], [[Philips]] and [[Stryker]].{{citation needed|date=August 2016}} By 2018, the list of subscribing companies had grown to include [[Baxter International|Baxter]], [[Boston Scientific]] and [[Medtronic]], in addition to the initial subscribing companies. 

In 2014, the initial technical Task Groups were created in the critical process areas of Electronics – [[PCB Assembly|PCBAs]], Electronics – Cable and Wire Harness, [[Heat treating|Heat Treating]], [[Sterilization (microbiology)|Sterilization]] and [[Welding]].  The Plastics Task Group and [[Process Validation]] sub-team were created in 2015.  By 2018, the list of critical process areas had grown to include [[Plastics extrusion|Plastics - Extrusion]], Plastics - [[Injection moulding|Injection Molding]], Plastics - Mechanical Assembly, Electronics - Printed Boards (Bare Boards), and Sterile Device Packaging as well. 

The first MedAccred accreditation was issued to Solar Atmospheres of Souderton, PA (USA) for [[Heat treating|Heat Treating]] in 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.todaysmedicaldevelopments.com/article/medaccred-solar-atmospheres-medical-device-manufacturing-accreditation-51915/|title=Solar Atmospheres receives 1st MedAccred accreditation|last=|first=|date=19 May 2015|website=Today's Medical Developments|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>. The US [[Food and Drug Administration|FDA]] subsequently recognized the Aerospace Heat Treating Standard AMS 2750, which is published by [[SAE International]] and used by MedAccred<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medtech.pharmaintelligence.informa.com/MT105137/Aerospace-Heat-Treating-Standard-Recognized-By-US-FDA-Giving-Nudge-To-MedAccred-SupplierControl-Prog|title=Aerospace Heat Treating Standard Recognized By US FDA, Giving Nudge To MedAccred Supplier-Control Program|last=Schmitt|first=Shawn|date=11 July 2017|website=MedTech Insight|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>. 

Accreditations have since been granted to companies in Mexico, Costa Rica, China, United Kingdom, France, Romania, Austria and Malaysia as well.

MedAccred was added to the [[AdvaMed]] Resource Center, Case for Quality Library in August 2015<ref>http://advamed.org/res</ref> and has since been noted in a number of industry publications as being a significant activity for the [[Medical device|medical devices]] industry<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.powertransmission.com/issues/0318/medaccred.pdf|title=MedAccred Rising to Ubiquity|last=Cannella|first=Alex|date=March 2018|website=Power Transmission magazine|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.devicemed.fr/dossiers/reglementation/medaccred-un-train-a-prendre-en-marche-pour-les-europeens/15724?utm_content=article&utm_medium=mail&utm_campaign=newsletter-20180502&utm_source=newsletter|title=MedAccred: A Train to be Taken for Europeans|last=Renard|first=Patrick|date=30 April 2018|website=Device Med|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cdn.p-r-i.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/22142930/MedAccred-feature-article-Medtech-Insight_v2.pdf|title=A Stronger Supply Chain: Stryker Tying Process Vendors to MedAccred; Others May Follow Suit as FDA Takes Notice|last=Schmitt|first=Shawn|date=August 2017|website=MedTech Insight|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>. The US Federal Government has been supportive of the MedAccred program, investing in the preparedness of the supply chain for the MedAccred audit and accreditation process<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.genedge.org/2017/09/19/genedge-awarded-federal-funding-medaccred-project/|title=GENEDGE Awarded Federal Funding For MedAccred Project|last=Priddy|first=Mindy|date=19 September 2017|website=Genedge|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> and setting up the MedMMAP (Medical Manufacturers MedAccred Accreditation Pathway) to support this effort<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medmmap.org/|title=MedMMAP|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>.

