'''Vince D. Calhoun''' is a brain imaging acquisition and analysis expert who has created numerous algorithms for making sense of complex brain imaging data. He is the creator of the group independent component analysis algorithm,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Calhoun |first1=V.D. |last2=Adali |first2=T. |last3=Pearlson |first3=G.D. |last4=Pekar |first4=J.J. |title=A method for making group inferences from functional MRI data using independent component analysis |url=http://mialab.mrn.org/software/gift/publications/2001_HBM_GroupICA_reprint.pdf |journal=Human Brain Mapping |date=November 2001 |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=140–151 |doi=10.1002/hbm.1048 |pmid=11559959|citeseerx=10.1.1.467.1625 }}</ref> which has become widely used for extracting 'networks' of coherent activity from functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) data. He was also an early innovator in approaches to characterizes the dynamics of brain connectivity<ref>{{cite journal |title=A method for evaluating dynamic functional network connectivity and task-modulation: application to schizophrenia |journal=Magnetic Resonance Materials in Physics, Biology and Medicine|volume=23|issue=5–6|pages=351–66|pmid=20162320|pmc=2891285|year=2010|last1=Sakoğlu|first1=U|last2=Pearlson|first2=G. D|last3=Kiehl|first3=K. A|last4=Wang|first4=Y. M|last5=Michael|first5=A. M|last6=Calhoun|first6=V. D|doi=10.1007/s10334-010-0197-8}}</ref>. He has also developed techniques to link many different types of data, called 'data fusion' including various types of brain imaging (structural, functional, connectivity) with genomic and epigenomic data<ref>{{cite journal |title=Feature based fusion of medical imaging data |journal=IEEE Transactions on Information Technology in Biomedicine|volume=13|issue=5|pages=711–20|pmid=19273016|pmc=2737598|year=2009|last1=Calhoun|first1=V. D|last2=Adali|first2=T|doi=10.1109/TITB.2008.923773}}</ref>. A key focus of Calhoun's work is the development of tool to identify brain imaging markers to help identify and potentially treat various brain disorders including schizophrenia, bipolar disorder, autism, Alzheimer's disease, and many more<ref>{{cite journal |title=Single subject prediction of brain disorders in neuroimaging: Promises and pitfalls |journal=NeuroImage|volume=145|issue=Pt B|pages=137–165|pmid=27012503|pmc=5031516|year=2017|last1=Arbabshirani|first1=M. R|last2=Plis|first2=S|last3=Sui|first3=J|last4=Calhoun|first4=V. D|doi=10.1016/j.neuroimage.2016.02.079}}</ref>

Calhoun is currently the President of the Mind Research Network<ref>{{cite web |title=The Mind Research Network |url=http://www.mrn.org}}</ref> and a Distinguished Professor of Electrical and Computer Engineering at the University of New Mexico.<ref>{{cite web |title=The University of New Mexico |url=http://www.unm.edu}}</ref>

